Feature: Backend logging and Grafana observability

Contract IDs
- None (cross-cutting observability feature affecting existing backend behavior, not introducing a client API contract)

Overview
- Add comprehensive, structured logging across all backend services.
- Introduce explicit log levels and event categories.
- Make logs visible in Grafana in addition to existing metrics and traces.

Role collaboration
- `@backend-dev`, `@devops`, `@security-specialist`, `@testing-engineer`, `@performance-engineer`, `@business-analyst`

Functional requirements
- `FR-001`: All backend services MUST emit structured logs for endpoint/resource calls.
- `FR-002`: All backend services MUST log Hibernate transaction lifecycle events at defined levels.
- `FR-003`: Entity create/update/delete/load operations MUST have category-based logs where operationally useful.
- `FR-004`: Session state transitions and auth-related session checks MUST be logged in services that manage sessions.
- `FR-005`: Servlet/JAX-RS filter decisions MUST be logged with enough context to debug auth, cookie, and request rejection paths.
- `FR-006`: SQL logging MUST support three detail modes:
  - short summary (`INFO`)
  - longer statement/debug context (`DEBUG`)
  - failure/error logging (`ERROR`)
- `FR-007`: Log categories MUST be documented and consistent across services.
- `FR-008`: Grafana MUST be able to query backend logs by service, level, and category.
- `FR-009`: Existing logging and existing Hibernate logging outputs MUST be reformatted to the shared structured format (no unstructured fallback by default).
- `FR-010`: Hibernate log subtypes MUST remain routed to different log files (for example transaction vs SQL vs statistics categories), and MUST NOT be merged into one file.
- `FR-011`: New logging categories introduced by this feature MUST follow the same per-category/per-type file separation rule.

Log category requirements
- `LOG-ENDPOINT`: request start/end, method, path, duration, status
- `LOG-HIBERNATE-TX`: transaction begin/commit/rollback, timing, failures
- `LOG-ENTITY`: entity mutation/load summaries
- `LOG-SESSION`: login/session creation, expiry, invalidation, validation failure
- `LOG-SQL`: query summary, slow query details, statement errors
- `LOG-FILTER`: cookie/auth/ciphertext/request filter decisions and reasons

Log level rules
- `ERROR`: failed request, rollback, exception, rejected critical auth path, failed SQL
- `WARN`: suspicious or degraded but recoverable condition
- `INFO`: normal operational lifecycle events and short summaries
- `DEBUG`: detailed diagnostic state and longer SQL/entity/filter detail
- `TRACE`: optional deep diagnostics, disabled by default in normal environments

Security requirements
- `SEC-001`: Logs MUST NOT expose raw secrets, passwords, payment nonces, or sensitive session tokens.
- `SEC-002`: Logs MUST redact or suppress sensitive headers/cookies where needed.
- `SEC-003`: Session/auth logs MUST remain useful without leaking credential material.

Non-functional requirements
- `NFR-001`: Default logging volume MUST be production-safe and not require DEBUG for normal operations insight.
- `NFR-002`: DEBUG/TRACE logging MUST be selectively configurable by service/category.
- `NFR-003`: Log ingestion and dashboard queries MUST remain performant under normal service load.
- `NFR-004`: Grafana log visualization MUST include filtering by service, level, and category.

Acceptance criteria
- [ ] All four backend services have documented logging level/category policy.
- [ ] Endpoint, Hibernate, entity, session, SQL, and filter events are covered.
- [ ] Sensitive values are redacted or omitted.
- [ ] Grafana can visualize/query backend logs.
- [ ] Default INFO/WARN/ERROR mode is useful without excessive noise.
- [ ] Existing logs and Hibernate logs are emitted in the agreed structured format.
- [ ] Hibernate log types and new logging categories are split into separate log files per configured routing.

Definition of Done
- [ ] Feature has spec, implementation, and tests.
- [ ] `@testing-engineer` verification done.
- [ ] `@security-specialist` verification done.
- [ ] `@performance-engineer` verification done.
